new exhibit of chinese fishing village at hopkins sulair sulair home searchworks e journals databases off campus access ask us sulair news logo sulair news home all articles submit article search sulair news library web sites searchworks databases az socrates google books google scholar search this site sulair news about sulair news back issues get email announcements submit article user login login with your sunet id home groups sulair news new exhibit of chinese fishing village at hopkins before hopkins seaside laboratory moved from lover's point to its current location and was renamed hopkins marine station the site had been occupied by a large community of chinese families who fished for things like abalone and squid unlike most chinese communities of the time who were primarily male with maybe one or two female prostitutes this village was made up of husbands and wives whose children born in the united states were the first chinese americans for the area the village was established in the early 1850's and was here for half a century until it burnt down in 1906 michael croft an experienced builder of model boats has recreated a model of the village based on the numerous photos of the village available from the miller library scrapbooks the california history room in the monterey public library and the california views historical photo collection of pat hathaway michael also visited the site as it currently exists here at hopkins in thanks for the help the miller library and the station provided he has loaned the model to us to display for a month attached are a couple of photos of the 32 x 51 model joe wible miller library hopkins marine station submitted by jwible stanford edu on mon 06 06 2011 12 15 back stanford university stanford california 94305 650 725 1064 terms of use copyright complaints
